<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-717-744  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 717 744.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Reseller News  July 30 1990 n379 p91(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Making inroads: peer-to-peer networking opens doors.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Shalvoy, Mary Lee.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Peer-to-peer networks, in which any workstation can act as both aserver and a workstation, offer a low-cost networking alternativefor small- to mid-sized businesses and workgroups interested insharing expensive peripherals, exchanging data, and having accessto a basic electronic mail system.andP;  Among the characteristics thatmake peer-to-peer networking more economical than traditionalproprietary networks is the simplicity of implementation thateliminates the need for a network manager.andP;  Peer-to-peernetworking products are available form such firms as Artisoft,which has an exclusive arrangement with Ingram Micro D todistribute LANtastic, Artisoft's network operating system, andDigital Communications Associates Inc. A LANtastic starter kit forconnecting two computers provides all the necessary hardware andsoftware for $525.andP;  Additional nodes can be added for $249 each,and include a card and a cable.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Artisoft Inc. (marketing).andO;Product:   Lantastic NOS (Computer network software) (marketing).andO;Topic:     Small BusinessConnectivityLocal Area NetworksLow CostMarket Entry.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>